# Download the needed libraries
library(data.table) #to read the data
library(caret) # to process the data
library(kableExtra)# to create tables
library(neuralnet) # for neural networks
library(forecast) # predict and accuracy
library(ggplot2) #plots
library(cowplot) #organising plots
df <- fread("ToyotaCorolla.csv") #import the dataset
df2<- as.data.frame(df[,c("Price", "Age_08_04", "KM","Fuel_Type", "HP", "Automatic", "Doors", "Quarterly_Tax", "Mfr_Guarantee", "Guarantee_Period", "Airco", "Automatic_airco", "CD_Player", "Powered_Windows", "Sport_Model", "Tow_Bar")]) # filtered the dataset to the variables recommended by the book
df2$Fuel_TypeP <- ifelse(df2$Fuel_Type == "Petrol", 1, 0) # we add a dummy for the kinds of  each car uses
df2$Fuel_TypeD <- ifelse(df2$Fuel_Type == "Diesel", 1, 0) 
df2$Fuel_TypeC <- ifelse(df2$Fuel_Type == "CNG", 1, 0) 
df2<-as.data.frame(df2[,-c(4,19)])# we drop the old fuel type variable and the dummy for CNG to avoid multicollinearity 
sapply(df2, function(x) length(unique(x)))# unique length of the variables

we introduced the dummies for the fuel variable and partition the data.

set.seed(1)  # controlled random numbers, to have the same samples when we re-run the code
training<- sample(row.names(df2), 0.6*dim(df2)[1]) #  training set 50% of the data
validation  <- sample(setdiff(row.names(df2), training ),  0.4*dim(df2)[1]) # validation set 30%
train.df<- df2[training,] # training set as individual data.frame
valid.df<- df2[validation,] # validation set as individual data.frame

We normalise the data:

train.norm.df <- train.df # initializing variables, for training set
valid.norm.df <-valid.df  # for validation set

normal.values <- preProcess(train.df[, c(1,2,3,4,6,7,9)], method=c("range")) # pre-processing training set
# method range scales the data to be within 0,1
train.norm.df[, c(1,2,3,4,6,7,9)]<- predict(normal.values, train.df[, c(1,2,3,4,6,7,9)]) #training set, numerical variables
valid.norm.df[, c(1,2,3,4,6,7,9)]<-  predict(normal.values, valid.df[, c(1,2,3,4,6,7,9)]) #validation set, numerical values

\(Normalized Value = (Value Min Value) / (Max Value Min Value)\)

To compute accuracy we need to scale back the price values and the predictions: So we need to multiply for \(max value - min value\) and add back \(max Value\). For the

ntw12_pred_t <- predict(ntw_1h_2n, train.norm.df)#predict on training data
ntw12_pred_v <- predict(ntw_1h_2n, valid.norm.df)#predict on validation data

min_value<-min(train.df$Price)   # re-call the minimal value of the price
max_value <- max(train.df$Price) # re-call the maximal value of the price

#we create a table with the records, predictions for the two sets, that we will scale back
rescaled_price_12<- data.table("Records_t" = train.norm.df$Price, "Predictions_t" = ntw12_pred_t ,"Records_v" = valid.norm.df$Price, "Predictions_v" = ntw12_pred_v)
rescaled_price_12 <- rescaled_price_12[, Records_t := Records_t*(max_value -  min_value) + min_value ] #re-scale the Records, in training set
rescaled_price_12 <- rescaled_price_12[, Predictions_t.V1 := Predictions_t.V1*(max_value -min_value) + min_value] #re-scale the Predictions, in training set
rescaled_price_12 <- rescaled_price_12[, Records_v := Records_v*(max_value -  min_value) + min_value ] #re-scale the Records, in validation set
rescaled_price_12 <- rescaled_price_12[, Predictions_v.V1 := Predictions_v.V1*(max_value -min_value) + min_value] #re-scale the Predictions, in validation set
rescaled_price_12 <- rescaled_price_12[, Residuals_t := Records_t - Predictions_t.V1] #compute the residuals and add a column, for the training set
rescaled_price_12 <- rescaled_price_12[, Residuals_v := Records_v - Predictions_v.V1] # for the validation set
head(rescaled_price_12)

With the 5 nodes and the 1 hidden layer the RMSE on the training set has decreased but the one on the validation set has increased. Meaning we are fitting better on the training set, but worse on the validation. The model seems to overfit a bit the training set. Compared to the first model, the 5 nodes seem to capture the relationship between predictors in the training set better, compromising the performance on the validation set.

This model instead brings down the disparity between the RMS errors for the predictions on the training and validation set. In fact, the rms error for the set up data has increased and the other has decreased, we are over-fitting the modelling data less. Therefore, making the model more adapt to predict prices for new sets of data.

What happens to the RMSE

11.3.a.i & ii

#we make frames for the plotting our RMSE measures
nn1<- data.frame("sets"=c("train", "Val"), "RMSE"= c(acc_12_train$RMSE, acc_12_val$RMSE))
nn2<- data.frame("sets"= c("train", "val"), "RMSE"=c(acc_15_train$RMSE,acc_15_val$RMSE))
nn3<- data.frame("sets"= c("train", "val"), "RMSE"=c(acc_25_train$RMSE, acc_25_val$RMSE))

rmse_12<-ggplot(nn1) + geom_col(aes(x=sets,y= RMSE, fill=RMSE), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("RMSE of network 1") #plot the 2 errors, in different colours
rmse_15<-ggplot(nn2) + geom_col(aes(x=sets,y= RMSE, fill=RMSE), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("RMSE of model 2")
rmse_25<- ggplot(nn3) + geom_col(aes(x=sets,y= RMSE, fill=RMSE), show.legend = F)+ theme_classic()+ ggtitle("RMSE of model 3")

plot_grid(rmse_12, rmse_15,rmse_25, ncol = 3) #organising the plots

We graphically observe how the different models,see gradually lower errors for the training set. But the validation set rmse does not decrease in any case. The last model in comparison slightly over-fits the set-up set.

Appropriate number of nodes and layers

11.3.a.iii

The first model all in all had the lowest difference in performance between the two sets, but with the biggest error for the training data. Too many nodes, might over-fit the data, but we observe that adding 2 layers brings down rmse for both sets, relative to the model with one layer with 5 nodes. But this 3rd model compared to the first one only has a lower Training set rmse, we deduce that this might be over-fitting the data. This confirms the idea that usually 1 hidden layer is enough for capturing the relationships between the predictors.
